#Lyrics
Eternal Father, strong to save, Whose arm hath bound the restless wave, Who bid'st the mighty ocean deep Its own appointed limits keep; O hear us when we cry to thee, For those in peril on the sea!  2. O Christ! Whose voice the waters heard And hushed their raging at thy word, Who walked'st on the foaming deep, And calm amidst its rage didst sleep; Oh hear us when we cry to thee, For those in peril on the sea!  3. Most Holy Spirit! Who didst brood Upon the chaos dark and rude, And bid its angry tumult cease, And give, for wild confusion, peace; Oh, hear us when we cry to thee For those in peril on the sea!  4. O Trinity of love and power! Our brethren shield in danger's hour; From rock and tempest, fire and foe, Protect them wheresoe'er they go; Thus evermore shall rise to thee, Glad hymns of praise from land and sea.  5. [Tags: ecumenical] Eternal Father, grant, we pray, To all Marines, both night and day, The courage, honor, strength, and skill Their land to serve, thy law fulfill; Be thou the shield forevermore From every peril to the Corps.  6. [Tags: ecumenical] Lord, guard and guide the men who fly Through the great spaces in the sky, Be with them always in the air, In dark'ning storms or sunlight fair. O, hear us when we lift our prayer, For those in peril in the air.  7. [Tags: ecumenical] Lord, stand beside the men who build And give them courage, strength, and skill. O grant them peace of heart and mind, And comfort loved ones left behind. Lord, hear our prayer for all Seabees, Where'er they be on land or sea.  8. [Tags: ecumenical] Lord God, our power evermore, Whose arm doth reach the ocean floor, Dive with our men beneath the sea; Traverse the depths protectively. O hear us when we pray, and keep Them safe from peril in the deep.  9. [Tags: ecumenical] O God, protect the women who, In service, faith in thee renew; O guide devoted hands of skill And bless their work within thy will; Inspire their lives that they may be Examples fair on land and sea.  10. [Tags: ecumenical] Creator, Father, who dost show Thy splendor in the ice and snow, Bless those who toil in summer light And through the cold Antarctic night, As they thy frozen wonders learn; Bless those who wait for their return.  11. [Tags: ecumenical] Eternal Father, Lord of hosts, Watch o'er the men who guard our coasts. Protect them from the raging seas And give them light and life and peace. Grant them from thy great throne above The shield and shelter of thy love.  12. [Tags: ecumenical] Eternal Father, King of birth, Who didst create the heaven and earth, And bid the planets and the sun Their own appointed orbits run; O hear us when we seek thy grace For those who soar through outer space.  13. [Tags: ecumenical] Creator, Father, who first breathed In us the life that we received, By power of thy breath restore The ill, and men with wounds of war. Bless those who give their healing care, That life and laughter all may share.  14. [Tags: ecumenical] God, who dost still the restless foam, Protect the ones we love at home. Provide that they should always be By thine own grace both safe and free. O Father, hear us when we pray For those we love so far away.  15. [Tags: ecumenical] Lord, guard and guide the men who fly And those who on the ocean ply; Be with our troops upon the land, And all who for their country stand: Be with these guardians day and night And may their trust be in thy might.  16. [Tags: ecumenical] O Father, King of earth and sea, We dedicate this ship to thee. In faith we send her on her way; In faith to thee we humbly pray: O hear from heaven our sailor's cry And watch and guard her from on high!  17. [Tags: ecumenical] And when at length her course is run, Her work for home and country done, Of all the souls that in her sailed Let not one life in thee have failed; But hear from heaven our sailor's cry, And grant eternal life on high!  18. O Christ, the Lord of hill and plain O'er which our traffic runs amain, By mountain pass or valley low, Wherever, Lord, thy brethren go; Protect them by thy guardian hand From every peril on the land.  19. O Spirit, Whom the Father send To spread abroad the firmament; O wind of heaven, by thy might, Save all who dare the eagle's flight; And keep them by thy watchful care From every peril in the air.

#Citations and References

Words: Stanzas 1–4: William Whiting, 1860. Stanza 5: J.E. Seim, 1966 (Marines). Stanza 6: naval aviation adaptation of Mary C.D. Hamilton, "Lord, Guard and Guide the Men Who Fly," 1915; adapted for Navy use during or shortly after World War II; these are the verses sung in the U.S. Navy, particularly naval aviation. Stanza 7: R.J. Dietrich, 1960 (Seabees/Construction Battalions). Stanza 8: David B. Miller, 1965 (Submariners). Stanza 9: lines 1–4 Merle E. Strickland, 1972, adapted James D. Shannon, 1973; lines 5–6 Beatrice M. Truitt, 1948 (Women in service). Stanza 10: L.E. Vogel, 1965 (Antarctic service). Stanza 11: author and date unknown (Coast Guard / coastal defense). Stanza 12: J.E. Volonte, 1961 (Space). Stanza 13: Galen H. Meyer, 1969, adapted James D. Shannon, 1970 (Medical / corpsmen). Stanza 14: Hugh Taylor, date unknown (Families / loved ones at home). Stanza 15: author unknown, c. 1955 (All branches combined). Stanzas 16–17: author and date unknown (Ship commissioning and decommissioning). Stanzas 18–19: Protestant Episcopal Church Hymnal, 1940; these are alternative second and third stanzas for land and air transportation, replacing the sea-focused originals.
Music: 'Melita' John Bacchus Dykes, 1861.
Setting: "Hymns Ancient and Modern", 1861.
copyright: public domain. Stanzas 1–4 public domain (Whiting d. 1878; Dykes d. 1876). Additional stanzas composed 1948–1972; copyright status of individual stanzas uncertain; reproduced from the Bureau of Naval Personnel publication via history.navy.mil.

Note on text variants: Stanzas 1–4 follow the history.navy.mil source text. Stanza 2 reads "didst sleep" (Christ asleep in the boat, Mark 4:38), correcting "didst keep" found in some printings including the Open Hymnal Project. Stanza 3 reads "Most Holy Spirit" and "chaos dark and rude"; some printings have "O Holy Spirit" and "waters dark and rude". Stanza 4 reads "Our brethren shield" and "wheresoe'er"; some printings (Open Hymnal Project) have "Our people shield" and "where'er they may go". The Presbyterian original of the aviators verse (Mary C.D. Hamilton, 1915, adapted 1943) ends with "O God, protect the men who fly, / Through lonely ways beneath the sky" rather than the Naval Aviation couplet used here.

